[medium] policies/secretsmanager_rotation_timeliness.rego:64 (correctness)
The bundle documents service-linked secrets as skipped for customer-managed rotation checks, and this policy already defines is_service_linked, but rotation_never_executed and rotation_overdue do not use it. A service-owned secret with owning_service set, rotation_enabled=true, and no last_rotated_date is still reported as rotation_never_executed even though rotation is AWS-managed for that resource.
Suggested fix: Add a service-linked skip_reason to secretsmanager_rotation_timeliness and gate both rotation_never_executed and rotation_overdue with not is_service_linked, matching secretsmanager_rotation_configured and the README/design intent.
Guidance: Fix policies/secretsmanager_rotation_timeliness.rego to match the deliberate design that service-linked secrets are skipped for customer-managed rotation checks. Add the same service-linked skip_reason shape used by policies/secretsmanager_rotation_configured.rego: when resource_type == "secret" and is_service_linked, return a message like Secret <arn> is service-linked (owning_service=<service>); rotation is AWS-managed. Gate both violation bodies with not is_service_linked: rotation_never_executed and rotation_overdue must not fire for owning_service != "". Be careful not to apply this skip to unrelated policies; KMS, replication, and tag-scoped posture intentionally still evaluate service-linked secrets. Add regression tests in policies/secretsmanager_rotation_timeliness_test.rego for a service-linked secret with rotation_enabled=true and empty last_rotated_date, and another with stale last_rotated_date/effective cadence, asserting no violations and that skip_reason is defined.
